&quot;NOT HAVING PAPERS IS NOT A CRIME AND DOES TAKE AWAY HUMAN RIGHTS&quot;" width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-8-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-8-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-8-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-8-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-8.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Near the El Chaparral Bridge, during the refugee march, Tijuana, November 25, 2018. The protest sign reads: &#8220;TO NOT HAVE PAPERS IS NOT A CRIME AND DOES NOT TAKE AWAY HUMAN RIGHTS.&#8221;</figcaption></figure><p><figure id="attachment_69204" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69204 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugees crossing the Tijuana River, November 2018. " width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69204 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugees crossing the Tijuana River, November 2018. " width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-4.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Refugee march, after crossing the Tijuana River, November 25, 2018.</figcaption></figure><p><figure id="attachment_69327" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69327 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugees at the Unidad Deportivo Benito Juárez, Barrio Zona Norte, Tijuana, November 25, 2018." width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69327 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugees at the Unidad Deportivo Benito Juárez, Barrio Zona Norte, Tijuana, November 25, 2018." width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-17.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Refugees at the Unidad Deportivo Benito Juárez, Barrio Zona Norte, Tijuana, November 25, 2018.</figcaption></figure><p><figure id="attachment_69205" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69205 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugee march, Tijuana, November 2018. The sign reads: WHY DO YOU CROSS OUR BORDERS? AND NOT LESS US CROSS YOURS?" width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69205 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugee march, Tijuana, November 2018. The sign reads: WHY DO YOU CROSS OUR BORDERS? AND NOT LESS US CROSS YOURS?" width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-5.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Refugee march, Tijuana, November 25, 2018. The sign reads: WHY DO YOU CROSS OUR BORDERS? AND NOT LET US CROSS YOURS.</figcaption></figure><p><figure id="attachment_69206" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69206 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugee march, Tijuana, November 2018. " width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69206 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugee march, Tijuana, November 2018. " width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-6.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Refugee march, Tijuana, November 25, 2018.</figcaption></figure><p><figure id="attachment_69212" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69212 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugees near the Ferrocarril Mexico rail yars, November 25, 2018." width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69212 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugees near the Ferrocarril Mexico rail yars, November 25, 2018." width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-12.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Refugees near the Ferrocarril Mexico rail yards, November 25, 2018.</figcaption></figure><p><p>It was at this fraught moment that hundreds of migrants gathered on the morning of Sunday November 25 for what was intended to be a peaceful march from the sports center to the San Ysidro crossing, where the Central Americans planned to present themselves to U.S. authorities and formally request asylum. The day was warm and sunny, and the marchers — including women wheeling strollers, young children carrying backpacks and toys — proceeded through several blocks of Zona Norte with residents looking on and international media in tow. Soon the march was halted by Mexican federal police officers, armed with helmets and riot shields, at the entrance to the El Chaparral Bridge on the south bank of the dry, channelized Tijuana River. A swarm of drones hovered overhead. The port of entry lay just across the bridge, a couple thousand feet away. After an uneventful standoff that lasted nearly an hour, the Central Americans pushed through the police lines, crossed the concrete riverbed, and spilled into the dense commercial zone surrounding the port. The Mexican police regrouped and barred entry to the southbound traffic lanes. Temporarily blocked, hundreds of migrants scattered through the network of streets and along the riverbank, attempting to approach the border facilities along the east and west sides of the San Ysidro complex.</p><blockquote class="pull left">The right to seek asylum is protected by U.S. and international law, and it is this right that drove the migrants northward.</blockquote><p>The march, and the migrants’ hopes for asylum, were surely doomed from the start. San Ysidro is the busiest land port in the western hemisphere, a sprawling complex where tens of thousands are processed daily through more than two dozen vehicle and pedestrian crossings. The right to seek asylum — part of the U.N. Declaration of Human Rights — is protected by both U.S. and international law, and it is this right that drove the migrants northward. TO NOT HAVE PAPERS IS NOT A CRIME AND DOES NOT TAKE AWAY HUMAN RIGHTS, read the banner of one young man in the march. Yet that fall San Ysidro was processing barely a few dozen asylum seekers each day. Earlier in the year the Trump administration had tightened the rules requiring migrants to apply only at official entry ports (rather than anywhere along the border); the bureaucratic euphemism is “metering” — an Obama-era emergency measure that the Trump administration has hardened into standard policy. <sup class="footnote_ref" id="footnote_10"><a href="#ref_10" title="Read Footnote 10">10</a></sup></p><p>In this grim context, what happened next seems almost inevitable. By late morning CBP agents began to shut down the U.S. side of the port; it would remain shut for several hours. Operations were halted and long lines of cars and trucks came to a standstill. U.S. military helicopters circled above. CBP agents in riot gear and U.S. soldiers in camouflage emerged in force, stringing razor wire across the entry lanes. Traffic was redirected and a P.A. system blared that the border crossing was temporarily closed and that travelers were forbidden to approach port facilities and that the use of force was authorized. On the Mexican side, the police stood firm while civilian laborers began erecting a series of interlocking steel barriers that quickly formed into an armored wall about eight-feet high. The 21st-century port was being sealed through the use of medieval techniques.</p><figure id="attachment_69213" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69213 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugees at the Unidad Deportivo Benito Juárez, barrio Zona Norte, near the border fence, November 25, 2018." width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69213 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13-1020x680.jpg" alt="Refugees at the Unidad Deportivo Benito Juárez, barrio Zona Norte, near the border fence, November 25, 2018." width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-13-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-