/placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-2-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-2.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Mexican police, near the San Ysidro Land Port of Entry, November 25, 2018.</figcaption></figure><p><figure id="attachment_69209" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69209 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-1020x680.jpg" alt="Southbound traffic lanes, San Ysidro Land Port, Tijuana, November 2018." width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69209 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-1020x680.jpg" alt="Southbound traffic lanes, San Ysidro Land Port, Tijuana, November 2018." width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-9.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Southbound traffic lanes, San Ysidro Land Port of Entry, Tijuana, November 25, 2018.</figcaption></figure><p><figure id="attachment_69203" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69203 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-1020x680.jpg" alt="A group of refugees break through the police line near the San Ysidro Land Port, Tijuana, November 2018." width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69203 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-1020x680.jpg" alt="A group of refugees break through the police line near the San Ysidro Land Port, Tijuana, November 2018." width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-3.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">A group of refugees break through the police line near the San Ysidro Land Port of Entry, Tijuana, November 25, 2018.</figcaption></figure><p><figure id="attachment_69211" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69211 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-1020x680.jpg" alt="Port vendor being arrested by the Mexican police, Tijuana, November 2018. " width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69211 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-1020x680.jpg" alt="Port vendor being arrested by the Mexican police, Tijuana, November 2018. " width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-11.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Port vendor being arrested by the Mexican police, Tijuana, November 25, 2018.</figcaption></figure><p><blockquote class="pull right">I felt the first effects of teargas while watching an impromptu soccer match being played by vendors in the emptied-out travel lanes of the port.</blockquote><p>I felt the first effects of teargas while watching an impromptu soccer match being played by food and souvenir vendors in the emptied-out travel lanes of the port. Border Patrol agents had earlier fired the canisters at migrants in the dry riverbed, and it was not long before men, women, and children were choking and crying, and trying to retreat. A half mile away, in the port lanes, the chemicals were potent enough to halt the game. Moments later, a group of Hondurans entered the vacant border crossing, and the vendors, irate over the closure, began pursuing the migrants. I lost sight of the soccer ball and watched as improvised weapons emerged — a baseball bat, a hammer, a lug wrench. The disorganized chase wound through tamale carts and taqueria stalls, moving into the green strip that separates the expedited and regular crossing lanes of the port and then onto a plaza where, on a typical day, a queue of taxis would be waiting.</p><p>By now the peaceful march had devolved into a chaotic melee. <sup class="footnote_ref" id="footnote_11"><a href="#ref_11" title="Read Footnote 11">11</a></sup> Taxi drivers were joining the crowd; a small group of Central Americans sought refuge in a parking lot but were barred entry by attendants; another group was standing atop an embankment that runs parallel to the rail yards where NAFTA-sanctioned freight trains await customs clearance. The Mexican police swarmed the streets on foot followed by a column of vans and pickup trucks. At which point the momentum quickly dissipated; nearly as dramatically as events had escalated, the Central Americans were loaded into vehicles and driven away.</p><p>This was the moment when that young man from Honduras turned to me and asked how to get across the border. Our exchange was cut short when he and his compatriots were picked up by Mexican police and taken back to the tent camp near the stadium. Within weeks, the camp was dismantled and many of the asylum seekers were relocated to a new shelter set up in a derelict nightclub on the southeastern edge of Tijuana — much farther from the border. <sup class="footnote_ref" id="footnote_12"><a href="#ref_12" title="Read Footnote 12">12</a></sup></p><figure id="attachment_69326" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69326 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-1020x1529.jpg" alt="" width="720" height="1079" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-1020x1529.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-580x870.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-768x1151.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-1025x1536.jpg 1025w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69326 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-1020x1529.jpg" alt="" width="720" height="1079" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-1020x1529.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-580x870.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-768x1151.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16-1025x1536.jpg 1025w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Tijuana-16.jpg 1360w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></noscript></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">San Ysidro Land Port of Entry, during the hours when the port, the busiest land crossing in the western hemisphere, was closed by the U.S. government.</figcaption></figure><p><blockquote class="pull left">Many saw in the migrant marchers a humanitarian crisis; the Trump administration saw a political opportunity.</blockquote><p>As I write, almost two years later, the repercussions from the tumultuous events in Tijuana in November 2018 continue to unfold. While many saw in the migrant marchers a humanitarian crisis — people fleeing violence from drug cartels or organized gangs or domestic partners, others seeking relief from virulent homophobia or transphobia, many trying to escape the entrenched poverty of corrupt states — the U.S. president saw a political opportunity. In early 2019 the Department of Homeland Security announced a new policy, the Migrant Protection Protocols, a.k.a. the “Remain in Mexico” program, which requires asylum seekers to stay south of the border during the many months when their cases are under review. The legality of the new rule was almost immediately challenged in a lawsuit led by the American Civil Liberties Union, but the notorious program, described by migrant rights advocates as a “dramatic undermining of the foundation of the U.S. asylum system,” remains in effect. <sup class="footnote_ref" id="footnote_13"><a href="#ref_13" title="Read Footnote 13">13</a></sup></p><p>To date tens of thousands have been denied asylum or discouraged from seeking it at all; currently thousands are stranded in Mexico. The so-called zero tolerance policy, which allowed family separations, was in force for much of 2019; the number of children who have been effectively orphaned will likely never be known. Meanwhile many who did enter the U.S. are being held in detention centers alongside those who have been swept up in immigration raids within the country. All of them, tens of thousands of people, have collided with the newest iterations of the Border-Security-Industrial Complex.</p><p>Many of those seeking asylum in the United States are from Honduras, Guatemala, and El Salvador, the Central American countries of the Northern Triangle; but sizable contingents come from China, Haiti, Cameroon, Romania, Bangladesh Ukraine, Angola, Congo — everywhere in the world. And these days an increasing number arrive from the Mexican state of Guerrero.</p><h2>3. El Tejocote, Guerrero, August 2019</h2><p>Marcos and Cecilia live close to the sky, more than 7,000 feet above sea level, on a north-facing ridge at the edge of their <em>campo</em> in the pueblo of El Tejocote. The tiny community, with just a few hundred souls, is located in Guerrero, in the midst of the Sierra Madre del Sur, some 130 miles east of the state capital, Chilpancingo, and worlds away from the coastal resort of Acapulco. A drone’s-eye view would show the mountainous terrain as a patchwork of cleared land and cloud forest, with stands of pine and oak giving way to fields planted with poppies and corn.</p><p>I spent several days with Marcos and Cecilia in their compound, a loose arrangement of small adobe structures with tin roofs, bordered by subsistence plots of corn, squash, and beans. Born and raised in El Tejocote, Marcos and Cecilia are both in their thirties; they built the place themselves and live there with their four children, Marcos’s father, a flock of chickens, and a cat. Vines of morning glory climb the adobe. Inside, the rooms are decorated with school portraits and silk flowers, and with images of the Virgin of Guadalupe, Jesus Christ, and Jesús Malverde, the legendary outlaw folk-hero known as the “angel of the poor,” and sometimes as the “narco-saint.”</p><figure id="attachment_69184" class="alignnone"><a class="zoom" href="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3.jpg"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden wp-image-69184 size-large" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-1020x680.jpg" alt="Sierra Made del Sur, Guerrero, August 2019." width="720" height="480" data-lazy-srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3.jpg 1360w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /><noscript><img class="wp-image-69184 size-large" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-1020x680.jpg" alt="Sierra Made del Sur, Guerrero, August 2019." width="720" height="480" srcset="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-1020x680.jpg 1020w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-580x387.jpg 580w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Taylor-Border-Gente-3-525x350.jpg 525w, https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/upload